== Clocking ==

A quartz crystal resonator on the N64 motherboard supplies the X'tal1 (X1) reference clock to the clock synthesizer (U7 or U17<ref>Early boards use the 8-pin Macronix MX8330MC at U7; later revisions substitute with equivalent MX9911MC. "Funtastic"-era and later models consolidate U7 and U15 into a single 14-pin MX8350 synthesizer at U17.</ref>) in order to generate the VI clock frequency (VCLK).

There are three video clock configurations corresponding to NTSC, PAL, and MPAL (a.k.a. [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PAL-M PAL-M]):

[[File:MX8350-Table.png|800px|Functional description, frequency table. Image from: [http://www.datasheet.hk/view_download.php?id=1145313&file=0069%5Cmx8350_566191.pdf IC-ON-LINE - Macronix MX8350 datasheet mirror]]]

[[File:MX8330 video maths.png|thumb|FSEL (frequency select) logic, clock math. Image from: [https://wiki.console5.com/tw/images/e/e3/MX8330.pdf Console5 - Macronix MX8330MC datasheet mirror]]]

Each X1 frequency is nominally defined as 4 times its respective regional colorburst frequency. These target "chrominance sub-carrier" frequencies are defined by international broadcast standards<ref>Nominal MPAL colorburst is precisely 511,312,500 ÷ 143 Hz; this is defined by relationship to the NTSC horizontal line frequency (<math>f_H</math>). (4,500,000 ÷ 286) × (909 ÷ 4) = (511,312,500 ÷ 143) = 3,575,611.888111888111... Hz</ref>:

[[File:CCIR-1990-Rep.624-4-Table.png|800px|alt=Colorburst: NTSC: 3,579,545 ± 10 Hz; MPAL: 3,575,611.49 ± 10 Hz ; PAL: 4,433,618.75 ± 5 Hz|Image from: [http://handle.itu.int/11.1004/020.1000/4.283 CCIR Report 624-4 (1990)]]]

Video clock frequency can be calculated using the following formula:

X1 × FSEL multiplier ÷ Output divider = VCLK

{| class="wikitable"
! Signal type !! X1 frequency !! FSEL state !! FSEL multiplier !! Output divider !! Resulting VCLK
|-
| NTSC || 14.31818 MHz || HIGH || 17 || 5 || 48.681818 MHz ± 30 ppm
|-
| PAL || 17.734475 MHz || LOW || 14 || 5 || 49.656530 MHz ± 30 ppm
|-
| MPAL || 14.30245 MHz || HIGH || 17 || 5 || 48.628322 MHz ± 30 ppm
|}

The [[Audio Interface]] also uses this clock.
 
== Precision ==

The Video DAC outputs 21-bit RGB color. Each pixel period transmits 28 bits (7 bits × 4 cycles), of which 21 bits are used for RGB data. Four of the remaining bits are used for control signaling during blanking; three bits are unused.<ref>Since there are three unused bits in the multiplex sequence, it is unclear why the DAC has only 7 bits of precision instead of 8, and no documentation already found explains this.</ref>

